IV. As regards the elements also I observe that pm„

they are accepted as being four in number: topmost the clement of fire, source of yonder eyes of all those blazing stars3 next the vapour which the Greeks and our own nation call by the same name, air—this is the principle of life, and penetrates all the universe and is intertwined with the whole; suspended by its force in the centre of space is poised the earth, and with it the fourth clement, that of the waters. Thus the mutual embrace of the unlike results in an interlacing‚ the light substances being prevented by the heavy ones from flying up, while on the contrary the heavy substances are held from crashing down by the upward tendency of the light ones. In this way owing to an equal urge in opposite directions the clements remain stationary, each in its own place, bound together by the unresting revolution of the world itself 3 and with this always running back to its starting-point‚ the earth is the lowest and central object in the whole, and stays suspended at the pivot of the universe and also balancing the bodies to which its suspension is due ; thus being alone motion- less with the universe revolving round her she both hangs attached to thern 311 311(1 31 1116 same time is that on which they all rest.
